Contents of https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/126574:
## Description

When a runtime-async caller `await`s a framework `async Task<T>` method (e.g., `DeflateStream.ReadAsync(byte[], int, int, CancellationToken)`), the JIT generates a **non-async FullOpts "thunk"** that wraps the result in a heap-allocated `Task<T>` via `CORINFO_HELP_NEWSFAST`. This causes a 72-byte allocation per call, even though the method completes synchronously and runtime-async should eliminate the allocation entirely.

This bug only manifests with **framework assembly** methods (e.g., `System.IO.Compression.dll`). The same pattern with user-defined code — including virtual calls across assemblies — produces **zero** allocations as expected.

## Reproduction

**Build:** `dotnet/runtime` at `ab2f538fca8` (current `main`) with `./build.sh clr+libs+libs.pretest -c Release` (runtime-async is on by default since [874cab5](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/commit/874cab52de071b64461fa74562e226a24557e5f8)).

**Test program** (compiled with `<Features>runtime-async=on</Features>`, targeting `net10.0`):

using System;
using System.IO;
using System.IO.Compression;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

var data \= new byte\[100\];
new Random(42).NextBytes(data);
var ms \= new MemoryStream();
using (var comp \= new DeflateStream(ms, CompressionLevel.Fastest, true))
    comp.Write(data, 0, data.Length);
var compressed \= ms.ToArray();

// Warmup
for (int i \= 0; i < 50; i++)
{
    var s \= new MemoryStream(compressed);
    using var d \= new DeflateStream(s, CompressionMode.Decompress);
    var b \= new byte\[data.Length\];
    await d.ReadAsync(b, 0, b.Length);       // Task<int>
    s \= new MemoryStream(compressed);
    using var d2 \= new DeflateStream(s, CompressionMode.Decompress);
    await d2.ReadAsync(b.AsMemory());        // ValueTask<int>
}

const int iters \= 10\_000;
long before;

// Task<int> path (ReadAsync(byte\[\], int, int))
before \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread();
for (int i \= 0; i < iters; i++)
{
    var s \= new MemoryStream(compressed);
    using var d \= new DeflateStream(s, CompressionMode.Decompress);
    var b \= new byte\[data.Length\];
    await d.ReadAsync(b, 0, b.Length);
}
long allocTask \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread() \- before;

// ValueTask<int> path (ReadAsync(Memory<byte>))
before \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread();
for (int i \= 0; i < iters; i++)
{
    var s \= new MemoryStream(compressed);
    using var d \= new DeflateStream(s, CompressionMode.Decompress);
    var b \= new byte\[data.Length\];
    await d.ReadAsync(b.AsMemory());
}
long allocVT \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread() \- before;

// Sync baseline
before \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread();
for (int i \= 0; i < iters; i++)
{
    var s \= new MemoryStream(compressed);
    using var d \= new DeflateStream(s, CompressionMode.Decompress);
    var b \= new byte\[data.Length\];
    d.Read(b, 0, b.Length);
}
long allocSync \= GC.GetAllocatedBytesForCurrentThread() \- before;

Console.WriteLine($"ReadAsync(byte\[\]):    {allocTask / iters} B/iter");
Console.WriteLine($"ReadAsync(Memory):    {allocVT / iters} B/iter");
Console.WriteLine($"Read(sync):           {allocSync / iters} B/iter");
Console.WriteLine();
Console.WriteLine($"Task overhead vs sync: {(allocTask \- allocSync) / iters} B  (expected: 0)");
Console.WriteLine($"VT overhead vs sync:   {(allocVT \- allocSync) / iters} B  (expected: 0)");

`.csproj`:

<Project Sdk\="Microsoft.NET.Sdk"\>
  <PropertyGroup\>
    <OutputType\>Exe</OutputType\>
    <TargetFramework\>net10.0</TargetFramework\>
    <NoWarn\>$(NoWarn);SYSLIB5007;CA2252</NoWarn\>
    <Features\>runtime-async=on</Features\>
  </PropertyGroup\>
</Project\>

Run with `corerun`:

```
corerun bin/Release/net10.0/repro.dll
```

## Actual output

```
ReadAsync(byte[]):    472 B/iter
ReadAsync(Memory):    400 B/iter
Read(sync):           400 B/iter

Task overhead vs sync: 72 B  (expected: 0)
VT overhead vs sync:   0 B  (expected: 0)
```

The `ValueTask<int>` path correctly has **zero** overhead vs sync. The `Task<int>` path has 72 B overhead (= one `Task<int>` allocation per call).

## Expected output

Both `Task<int>` and `ValueTask<int>` paths should have zero allocation overhead vs sync, since all methods in the call chain are `async` and the caller immediately `await`s the result.

## JIT evidence

With `DOTNET_JitDisasm=ReadAsync`, `DeflateStream.ReadAsync(byte[])` gets **two** JIT compilations:

1.  **FullOpts thunk** — returns `Task<int>`, is NOT marked `async`, contains `CORINFO_HELP_NEWSFAST`:

    ```
    ; Assembly listing for method DeflateStream:ReadAsync(byte[],int,int,CancellationToken):Task`1[int]:this (FullOpts)
    ; FullOpts code
    ; optimized code            <-- NOT "async"
    ...
           mov      rdi, 0x7F20A1E1BE60
           call     CORINFO_HELP_NEWSFAST       <-- allocates Task<int>
           mov      r15, rax
           mov      dword ptr [r15+0x34], 0x1000000
           mov      dword ptr [r15+0x38], ebx   <-- stores result into Task
    ```

2.  **Tier0 async entrypoint** — returns `int`, IS marked `async`:

    ```
    ; Assembly listing for method DeflateStream:ReadAsync(byte[],int,int,CancellationToken):int:this (Tier0)
    ; async
    ```


The caller dispatches to the FullOpts thunk instead of the async entrypoint, causing the unnecessary allocation.

## Environment

*   OS: Linux (Fedora 43), x86-64
*   Runtime: `dotnet/runtime` at `ab2f538fca8` (main), built with `./build.sh clr+libs+libs.pretest -c Release`
*   SDK: 11.0.100-preview.3
*   Runtime-async enabled via [874cab5](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/commit/874cab52de071b64461fa74562e226a24557e5f8)

